{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_e813165784c64a51bb38d39f","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# OS X Setup\n2\t\n3\tThis guide details the steps to set up Huxley on OS X. Use this if you'd like to customize your setup, or had trouble with the setup script.\n4\t\n5\t### Virtualenv\n6\tVirtualenv separates your project's Python modules from the rest of your system to prevent conflicts. We'll install virtualenv and a useful utility built on top of it, virtualenvwrapper.\n7\t\n8\t    $ sudo pip install virtualenv\n9\t    $ sudo pip install virtualenvwrapper\n10\t\n11\tAdd the following two lines to your `.bash_profile` and source it:\n12\t\n13\t    export WORKON_HOME=\"$HOME/.virtualenvs\"\n14\t    source /usr/local/bin/virtualenvwrapper.sh\n15\t\n16\t    # And in terminal:\n17\t    $ source ~/.bash_profile\n18\t\n19\tYou'll then be able to create a virtualenv for Huxley:\n20\t\n21\t    $ mkvirtualenv huxley\n22\t\n23\tFrom now on, whenever you're going to work on Huxley, just remember to switch to your `huxley` virtualenv (and deactivate it when you're done):\n24\t\n25\t    $ workon huxley # When you're about to begin work\n26\t    ...hack...\n27\t    $ deactivate # After you're done\n28\t\n29\t### Hub\n30\tHub is a command line interface to GitHub. It's optional for Huxley, but it certainly makes issuing pull requests easier. Install it using Homebrew, with\n31\t\n32\t    $ brew install hub\n33\t\n34\t### Create a Fork and Clone\n35\tBegin by creating a fork of this repository. Go to the top-right of this repository page and click \"Fork\" (read Github's [guide](http://help.github.com/forking/) for a refresher on forking. If you're new to GitHub, remember to [set up SSH keys](https://help.github.com/articles/generating-ssh-keys) as well). Then, clone your repository, `cd` into it, and add this one as an upstream remote:\n36\t\n37\t    $ git clone git@github.com:yourusername/huxley.git\n38\t    $ cd huxley\n39\t    $ git remote add upstream https://github.com/kmeht/huxley.git\n40\t\n41\tNext, configure your author information. Use your name and email as they appear on GitHub:\n42\t\n43\t    $ git config user.name \"Your Name\"\n44\t    $ git config user.email \"your@github.email\"\n45\t\n46\t### Install Dependencies\n47\tInstall the Python dependencies with the provided `requirements.txt` (remember to activate the `huxley` virtualenv!):\n48\t\n49\t    $ pip install -r requirements.txt\n50\t    \n51\tInstall the JS dependencies with the provided `package.json` using npm:\n52\t\n53\t    $ npm install\n54\t\n55\t### Initial Setup\n56\tThe first step is to prepare the database. We do that by running: \n57\t\n58\t    $ python manage.py runserver\n59\t\n60\tRunning the server will automatically create a database for us at `huxley/huxley.db`. Once you've run the server exit it (CONTROL-C), and then run:\n61\t\n62\t    $ python manage.py migrate\n63\t    $ python manage.py loaddata conference countries committees advisor chair\n64\t\n65\tFinally, we use Pipeline to collect, compile, and compress our static assets. It simply hooks into Django's `collectstatic` management command:\n66\t\n67\t    $ python manage.py collectstatic --noinput\n68\t    \n69\tIf you run into an error here run `ulimit -n 512`. This will increase the number of files the process running Huxley will be allowed to open.\n70\t\n71\tNext, you need to compile your JS code by running:\n72\t\n73\t    $ npm run build\n74\t\n75\tLastly, open up a new tab in your terminal (make sure you're still in your virtualenv), and spin up a development server:\n76\t\n77\t    $ python manage.py runserver\n78\t\n79\tYou can access Huxley at `localhost:8000`.\n80\t\n81\t\n82\tIf you haven't created a superuser yet, you should do that now:\n83\t\n84\t    $ python manage.py createsuperuser\n85\t    \n86\tYour superuser credentials is what will allow you to login to the admin panel at `localhost:8000/admin/`.\n87\t\n88\tTo check out the other management commands at your disposal run `python manage.py`. This will list out all possible management commands. Many of these commands will be useful to keep your development environment in check.\n89\t\n90\tWith that, you're ready to go; start hacking!\n91\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57c0b579-c617-43af-a22b-565dc946c318","uuid":"91eb030a-5fce-405b-8ad6-6e9b5c3eca9a","timestamp":"2026-04-08T21:38:14.976Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/setup/OSX.md","content":"# OS X Setup\n\nThis guide details the steps to set up Huxley on OS X. Use this if you'd like to customize your setup, or had trouble with the setup script.\n\n### Virtualenv\nVirtualenv separates your project's Python modules from the rest of your system to prevent conflicts. We'll install virtualenv and a useful utility built on top of it, virtualenvwrapper.\n\n    $ sudo pip install virtualenv\n    $ sudo pip install virtualenvwrapper\n\nAdd the following two lines to your `.bash_profile` and source it:\n\n    export WORKON_HOME=\"$HOME/.virtualenvs\"\n    source /usr/local/bin/virtualenvwrapper.sh\n\n    # And in terminal:\n    $ source ~/.bash_profile\n\nYou'll then be able to create a virtualenv for Huxley:\n\n    $ mkvirtualenv huxley\n\nFrom now on, whenever you're going to work on Huxley, just remember to switch to your `huxley` virtualenv (and deactivate it when you're done):\n\n    $ workon huxley # When you're about to begin work\n    ...hack...\n    $ deactivate # After you're done\n\n### Hub\nHub is a command line interface to GitHub. It's optional for Huxley, but it certainly makes issuing pull requests easier. Install it using Homebrew, with\n\n    $ brew install hub\n\n### Create a Fork and Clone\nBegin by creating a fork of this repository. Go to the top-right of this repository page and click \"Fork\" (read Github's [guide](http://help.github.com/forking/) for a refresher on forking. If you're new to GitHub, remember to [set up SSH keys](https://help.github.com/articles/generating-ssh-keys) as well). Then, clone your repository, `cd` into it, and add this one as an upstream remote:\n\n    $ git clone git@github.com:yourusername/huxley.git\n    $ cd huxley\n    $ git remote add upstream https://github.com/kmeht/huxley.git\n\nNext, configure your author information. Use your name and email as they appear on GitHub:\n\n    $ git config user.name \"Your Name\"\n    $ git config user.email \"your@github.email\"\n\n### Install Dependencies\nInstall the Python dependencies with the provided `requirements.txt` (remember to activate the `huxley` virtualenv!):\n\n    $ pip install -r requirements.txt\n    \nInstall the JS dependencies with the provided `package.json` using npm:\n\n    $ npm install\n\n### Initial Setup\nThe first step is to prepare the database. We do that by running: \n\n    $ python manage.py runserver\n\nRunning the server will automatically create a database for us at `huxley/huxley.db`. Once you've run the server exit it (CONTROL-C), and then run:\n\n    $ python manage.py migrate\n    $ python manage.py loaddata conference countries committees advisor chair\n\nFinally, we use Pipeline to collect, compile, and compress our static assets. It simply hooks into Django's `collectstatic` management command:\n\n    $ python manage.py collectstatic --noinput\n    \nIf you run into an error here run `ulimit -n 512`. This will increase the number of files the process running Huxley will be allowed to open.\n\nNext, you need to compile your JS code by running:\n\n    $ npm run build\n\nLastly, open up a new tab in your terminal (make sure you're still in your virtualenv), and spin up a development server:\n\n    $ python manage.py runserver\n\nYou can access Huxley at `localhost:8000`.\n\n\nIf you haven't created a superuser yet, you should do that now:\n\n    $ python manage.py createsuperuser\n    \nYour superuser credentials is what will allow you to login to the admin panel at `localhost:8000/admin/`.\n\nTo check out the other management commands at your disposal run `python manage.py`. This will list out all possible management commands. Many of these commands will be useful to keep your development environment in check.\n\nWith that, you're ready to go; start hacking!\n","numLines":91,"startLine":1,"totalLines":91}}}
